To align a row of divs to the right using flex in CSS, we can use the `justify-content` property with the value `flex-end`. Here's an example code snippet:


HTML:

```html
<div class="container">
  <div class="item">Item 1</div>
  <div class="item">Item 2</div>
  <div class="item">Item 3</div>
  <div class="item">Item 4</div>
</div>
```
CSS:
```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: flex-end;
}

.item {
  width: 100px;
  height: 100px;
  background-color: gray;
  margin: 5px;
}
```

In this example, the `.container` div has `display: flex`, which turns it into a flex container. The `justify-content: flex-end` property aligns all the items to the right side of the container.


You can also use other values for `justify-content` such as `center` or `space-between`. Here's an example with `center`:


```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
}
```

This will center the items in the middle of the container.


And here's an example using `space-between`:


```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between;
}
```

This will evenly distribute the items with equal spacing between them and to the edges of the container.
